# COMMENTS - Section 5 — Incoming Sample Dataclass (FoodSample)
# The input data structure for communication between sensor/hardware layer and the sorting engine. 
# Each food item arriving on the intake belt needs to be represented in terms of this class before sort_item() can take a look. Its five attributes correspond to the four criteria:

# food_type → used for looking up the FoodProfile (criteria 1 & 2)
# measured_temp_c → evaluated against the safe temperature range (criterion 2)
# hours_since_harvest → used to calculate freshness against shelf life (criterion 3)
# current_region → looked up in regional scores (criterion 4)
# item_id → passed straight through into the SortDecision class (criteria 0 & N/A)

# Feeds into: sort_item() accepts one FoodSample as an argument. Every edge-case handler needs it too so that they can copy item_id back into the SortDecision class for tracing purposes. 
# assess_food_condition() takes it as well to pass item_id back into the decision.


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 5 — INCOMING SAMPLE DATACLASS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# FoodSample is the input contract between the hardware/sensor layer and
# this sorting engine. Every item arriving on the intake belt must be
# described as a FoodSample before sort_item() is called.
#
# In a real system the vision pipeline, barcode scanner, and IR sensor
# populate these fields automatically. In this prototype, the simulated
# sensor layer in Section 12 generates them.

@dataclass
class FoodSample:
    """
    Represents a single food item arriving on the intake conveyor.

    Parameters
    ----------
    food_type           : key into FOOD_CATALOG — must match exactly
                          (e.g. "strawberry", "chicken_breast")
    measured_temp_c     : surface temperature from IR sensor in °C
    current_region      : Region enum for this facility's environment
    hours_since_harvest : hours elapsed since harvest / production date
                          (read from package label or RFID tag)
    item_id             : unique identifier for traceability (barcode / RFID)
    """
    food_type:           str
    measured_temp_c:     float
    current_region:      Region
    hours_since_harvest: float
    item_id:             str = "UNKNOWN"    # default for unlabelled items


# COMMENTS-Section 6 — Sort Decision Dataclass (SortDecision)
#The output data structure of our sorting engine — sort_item()'s return value. Only destination and action fields are needed by the hardware drivers; the rest are meant for monitoring/logging purposes:

# priority (1-10) defines sorting order; higher numbers mean earlier processing
# confidence (0.0 - 1.0) is the overall quality rating across all criteria; all <0.40 sorts go into quarantine automatically
# reason is a human-readable rationale for the decision; serves logging and user terminals
# condition is the FoodCondition set by the food assessment module (Section 6b)
# warnings list non-critical conditions that decreased confidence (may be empty for good sorts)

#Feeds into: execute_decision() (Section 11) uses both destination and action fields. print_dashboard() (Section 13) reads all fields for display purpose. sort_batch() (Section 10) sorts SortDecisions by priority.



# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 6 — SORT DECISION DATACLASS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SortDecision is the output contract — what sort_item() returns.
# Hardware drivers only need .destination and .action.
# Everything else supports monitoring, logging, and operator alerts.

@dataclass
class SortDecision:
    """
    Complete routing decision returned by sort_item().

    Fields
    ------
    item_id     : echoed from FoodSample — links the decision to a physical item
    destination : Bin enum — which bin/compartment to send the item to
    action      : Action enum — which physical mechanism to trigger
    priority    : 1 (lowest urgency) → 10 (must route immediately)
                  used by the belt controller to schedule execution order
    confidence  : 0.0–1.0 composite score across all four criteria
                  values below 0.40 are overridden to QUARANTINE
    reason      : human-readable explanation of why this decision was made
                  (for operator display and audit logs)
    warnings    : list of non-fatal issues that reduced confidence
                  (empty list = clean sort with no concerns)
    """
    item_id:     str
    destination: Bin
    action:      Action
    priority:    int            # 1–10
    confidence:  float          # 0.0–1.0
    reason:      str
    condition:   "FoodCondition" = None   # set by assess_food_condition() after sort_item()
    warnings:    list[str] = field(default_factory=list)    # mutable default needs field()

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# COMMENTS-Section 6b — Food Condition Assessment (FoodCondition, assess_food_condition)

# This section was added in this update to resolve the basic question "What condition is this item in?".
# FoodCondition is an enumerated type with five possible states — GOOD, USE SOON, EXPIRING SOON, CRITICAL, and BAD — each having an associated operator command in the CONDITION_ACTIONS and terminal symbol in CONDITION_SYMBOLS dicts.
# assess_food_condition() requires three pre-computed parameters passed from sort_item() — remaining fraction of shelf life (0–1.0), temperature safety rating (same scale), and destination bin — then evaluates nine rules with strict ordering:
# Routed into the REJECT bin already → always BAD (exhaustively checked for separate messages in each case)
# Temp safety < 0.0 → BAD
# Remaining fraction < 0.0 → BAD
# Temp safety = 0.0 and fraction < 0.2 → CRITICAL (both signals red)
# Fraction < 0.1 → CRITICAL
# Fraction < 0.3 → EXPIRING SOON
# Temp safety = 0.0 and fraction > 0.1 → EXPIRING SOON (temp stress decreases effective life)
# Fraction > 0.3 and temp safety > 0.0 → USE SOON
# Fraction > 0.6 and temp safety > 0.0 → GOOD
# Helper method _get_shelf_hours() is a small look-up function for retrieving the number of hours from the shelf life in FOOD_CATALOG for the "days to expiry" field in the message string.
# Feeds into: sort_item() invokes the method at Step 8 for any item sorted normally. 
# Four edge-case handlers set condition explicitly in their returned SortDecisions (no matter how; they always know which it should be — BAD or CRITICAL). 
# print_dashboard() accesses d.condition for displaying the symbol in each line.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 6b — FOOD CONDITION ASSESSMENT
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# This section answers the plain question an operator wants to see on screen:
# "Is this item GOOD, EXPIRING SOON, or BAD?"
#
# It is deliberately separate from the sort decision engine because condition
# is a human-facing label, not a routing criterion. The sort engine already
# makes routing decisions based on raw numeric scores; this section translates
# those numbers into a clear, colour-coded status for display on operator
# terminals, SCADA dashboards, and printed labels.
#
# Three inputs drive the condition label:
#   1. remaining_fraction  — how much of the shelf life is left (0.0–1.0)
#   2. temp_ok             — whether the current temperature is in the safe range
#   3. destination         — if the sort engine already sent it to REJECT,
#                            the condition is always BAD regardless of freshness
#
# The five condition levels, from best to worst:
#   GOOD          → >60 % shelf life remaining, safe temperature
#   USE_SOON      → 30–60 % remaining — still fine but use before new stock
#   EXPIRING_SOON → 10–30 % remaining — elevated urgency, consume or freeze now
#   CRITICAL      → <10 % remaining OR borderline temperature — last chance
#   BAD           → expired, unsafe temperature, or already rejected

class FoodCondition(str, Enum):
    """
    Human-readable quality label for a food item.
    Each level maps to a clear operator message and a suggested action.
    """
    GOOD          = "GOOD"           # fresh, plenty of life left, safe temp
    USE_SOON      = "USE SOON"       # aging but still fully safe, prioritise use
    EXPIRING_SOON = "EXPIRING SOON"  # approaching end of life — escalate handling
    CRITICAL      = "CRITICAL"       # very little life left or borderline temp
    BAD           = "BAD"            # expired, unsafe temp, or already rejected


# Recommended operator action for each condition level.
# This is printed in the dashboard and can be relayed to warehouse staff.
CONDITION_ACTIONS: dict[FoodCondition, str] = {
    FoodCondition.GOOD:          "Store normally. No special handling required.",
    FoodCondition.USE_SOON:      "Place at front of storage. Use before newer stock.",
    FoodCondition.EXPIRING_SOON: "Route to high-turnover zone. Flag for rapid dispatch.",
    FoodCondition.CRITICAL:      "Use immediately or freeze if applicable. Alert supervisor.",
    FoodCondition.BAD:           "Remove from food chain. Log and dispose per protocol.",
}

# Terminal display symbols used in the dashboard — one character per level.
CONDITION_SYMBOLS: dict[FoodCondition, str] = {
    FoodCondition.GOOD:          "✔",   # green check
    FoodCondition.USE_SOON:      "→",   # neutral arrow
    FoodCondition.EXPIRING_SOON: "⚠",   # warning triangle
    FoodCondition.CRITICAL:      "!!",  # double exclamation
    FoodCondition.BAD:           "✘",   # red cross
}


def assess_food_condition(
    sample:             FoodSample,
    remaining_fraction: float,      # output of _score_perishability: 0.0–1.0
    temp_score:         float,      # output of _score_temperature: 0.0, 0.5, or 1.0
    destination:        Bin,        # final routed destination from sort_item()
) -> tuple[FoodCondition, str]:
    """
    Classify the food item's condition into one of five human-readable levels.

    This function is called inside sort_item() after all scoring is complete,
    so it has access to every computed value. It does NOT change any routing
    decision — it only attaches a label for operator display.

    Parameters
    ----------
    sample             : the original FoodSample (used for item_id in log output)
    remaining_fraction : fraction of shelf life remaining (1.0 = brand new,
                         0.0 = exactly at expiry, <0 clamped to 0)
    temp_score         : temperature score from _score_temperature()
                         1.0 = safe | 0.5 = borderline | 0.0 = unsafe/rejected
    destination        : the bin the engine has already chosen for this item

    Returns
    -------
    condition   : FoodCondition enum value
    description : one-sentence plain-English description for display
    """

    # ── Rule 1: Already rejected → always BAD ─────────────────────────────
    # If the sort engine sent the item to the reject chute, the condition is
    # definitively BAD. This covers both expired items (remaining_fraction = 0)
    # and unsafe temperature items (temp_score = 0.0). No further checks needed.
    if destination == Bin.REJECT:
        if remaining_fraction <= 0.0:
            desc = (
                f"Item has exceeded its shelf life "
                f"({sample.hours_since_harvest:.1f} h elapsed). "
                f"Must be removed from the food chain."
            )
        else:
            desc = (
                f"Item is at an unsafe temperature and has been rejected. "
                f"May have partially spoiled — do not consume."
            )
        return FoodCondition.BAD, desc

    # ── Rule 2: Unsafe temperature (not yet expired) → BAD ────────────────
    # temp_score 0.0 means the temperature reading is fully outside the safe
    # window. Even if the item is fresh, temperature abuse may have already
    # begun microbial growth — classify as BAD.
    if temp_score == 0.0:
        desc = (
            f"Temperature reading is outside the safe storage range. "
            f"Potential spoilage regardless of freshness — treat as BAD."
        )
        return FoodCondition.BAD, desc

    # ── Rule 3: Shelf life already gone → BAD ─────────────────────────────
    # remaining_fraction <= 0 means hours_since_harvest >= shelf_life_hours.
    # This duplicates the reject check only as a safety net in case condition
    # is assessed on a quarantined item that is also expired.
    if remaining_fraction <= 0.0:
        desc = (
            f"Shelf life fully consumed. Item is expired and must be discarded."
        )
        return FoodCondition.BAD, desc

    # ── Rule 4: Borderline temperature + low remaining life → CRITICAL ─────
    # When temp_score is 0.5 (borderline) AND less than 20 % of shelf life
    # remains, the combination is critical: temperature stress on an already
    # aging item dramatically accelerates spoilage. Flag immediately.
    if temp_score == 0.5 and remaining_fraction < 0.20:
        pct = round(remaining_fraction * 100)
        desc = (
            f"Borderline temperature combined with only {pct} % shelf life remaining. "
            f"High spoilage risk — consume or freeze immediately."
        )
        return FoodCondition.CRITICAL, desc

    # ── Rule 5: Very little shelf life left → CRITICAL ────────────────────
    # Less than 10 % remaining regardless of temperature.
    # "10 %" is the threshold because at this level even a minor temperature
    # fluctuation or handling delay could push the item over the edge.
    if remaining_fraction < 0.10:
        pct = round(remaining_fraction * 100)
        desc = (
            f"Only {pct} % of shelf life remaining. "
            f"Item is in critical condition — use immediately or discard."
        )
        return FoodCondition.CRITICAL, desc

    # ── Rule 6: Approaching end of life → EXPIRING SOON ──────────────────
    # 10–30 % shelf life remaining. The item is still safe to consume but
    # should be prioritised over fresher stock to avoid waste.
    if remaining_fraction < 0.30:
        pct = round(remaining_fraction * 100)
        desc = (
            f"{pct} % of shelf life remaining. "
            f"Expiring soon — prioritise for immediate use or dispatch."
        )
        return FoodCondition.EXPIRING_SOON, desc

    # ── Rule 7: Borderline temperature but still fresh → EXPIRING SOON ────
    # Even with plenty of time left, a borderline temperature reading is a
    # yellow flag — storage conditions are marginal and the item should be
    # monitored and used before other stock. Classify as EXPIRING_SOON rather
    # than USE_SOON to elevate the urgency signal.
    if temp_score == 0.5:
        pct = round(remaining_fraction * 100)
        desc = (
            f"Temperature is near the safe-range boundary. "
            f"{pct} % shelf life remains, but temperature stress may shorten it. "
            f"Prioritise use."
        )
        return FoodCondition.EXPIRING_SOON, desc

    # ── Rule 8: Aging but still fully safe → USE SOON ─────────────────────
    # 30–60 % shelf life remaining, temperature fully safe.
    # Item is in normal mid-cycle condition. No alarm, but it should be
    # consumed before newer stock to maintain FIFO rotation.
    if remaining_fraction < 0.60:
        pct = round(remaining_fraction * 100)
        days_left = round((remaining_fraction * _get_shelf_hours(sample)) / 24, 1)
        desc = (
            f"{pct} % of shelf life remaining (~{days_left} days). "
            f"Item is safe — place at front of storage for FIFO rotation."
        )
        return FoodCondition.USE_SOON, desc

    # ── Rule 9: Fresh and safe → GOOD ─────────────────────────────────────
    # More than 60 % of shelf life remaining and temperature fully within range.
    # This is the ideal case — no special handling required.
    pct = round(remaining_fraction * 100)
    days_left = round((remaining_fraction * _get_shelf_hours(sample)) / 24, 1)
    desc = (
        f"{pct} % of shelf life remaining (~{days_left} days). "
        f"Item is fresh and in good condition. Store normally."
    )
    return FoodCondition.GOOD, desc


def _get_shelf_hours(sample: FoodSample) -> float:
    """
    Helper: look up the shelf_life_hours for a sample's food type.
    Returns 0 if the food type is not in the catalog (unknown item).
    Used only for display calculations inside assess_food_condition().
    """
    profile = FOOD_CATALOG.get(sample.food_type.lower().strip())
    return profile.shelf_life_hours if profile else 0.0


# COMMENTS-Section 7 — Criterion Scoring Helpers
#Five scoring helper functions, each implementing the logic for exactly one criterion dimension and returning both a score (float between 0.0 and 1.0 inclusive) and a set of optional advisory warning messages.

#_score_temperature(profile, temp) — compares measured surface temperature against a food-specific safe range. Returns 1.0 if within safe temperature range, 0.5 if in "borderline" (±2 °C of border), and 0.0 otherwise (TemperatureRange.is_borderline()). 
#The latter case is the only hard safety trigger that guarantees automatic reject regardless of other scores.
#_score_perishability(profile, hours_since_harvest) — calculates remaining_percentage (a float between 0.0 and 1.0) using elapsed_time/shelf_life, then clamps it to 1.0. Calculates urgency (1...10) by multiplying perishability rating with remaining_percentage. 
#A 90% elapsed salmon fillet will have urgency=10, while canned beans at 1% will have urgency=1.
#_score_regional(profile, region) — simply queries the corresponding key in the food_profile['regional_scores'] dictionary, or returns 0.5 if the region is missing from it. Generates warning at scores below 0.4.
#_select_bin(profile, temp_score, regional_score) — iterates over the food's allowed_bins in specified order. Chooses the most suitable destination, drops bin confidence by 0.2 if the regional suitability is bad, or by 0.4 if both temperature is borderline (0.5) and a second-best option is available.
#_select_action(profile, destination, temp_score, urgency) — implements four prioritised rules to convert all information into a physical hardware command. 
# In priority order: bad temperature → reject chute, fragile → robotic arm, urgency >= 9 → stop conveyor, otherwise → passive diversion to lane.

#Feeds into: _select_action(), _score_temperature(), _score_perishability(), _score_regional(), _select_bin() — collectively used by sort_item() (Section 9) in Steps 1...5 of its pipeline. _score_perishability() additionally passes its remaining_fraction parameter directly into assess_food_condition() (Section 6b).



# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 7 — CRITERION SCORING HELPERS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# One function per sorting criterion. Each returns a numeric score
# (0.0–1.0) plus a list of any warnings generated.
# The weights below control how much each criterion contributes to
# the final composite confidence score.

# Weights must sum to 1.0
# Temperature is highest because it is a food-safety hard constraint.
# Destination compatibility is second — wrong bin = food lost or wasted.
# Perishability drives urgency scheduling more than confidence.
# Regional suitability is advisory — it informs long-term rationing decisions.
CRITERION_WEIGHTS = {
    "temperature":   0.35,  # primary food-safety dimension
    "destination":   0.30,  # compatibility with available bins
    "perishability": 0.20,  # freshness / remaining shelf life
    "regional":      0.15,  # environmental suitability (advisory)
}


def _score_temperature(profile: FoodProfile, temp: float) -> tuple[float, list[str]]:
    """
    Evaluate measured temperature against the food's safe range.

    Returns
    -------
    score : 1.0 = comfortably within range
            0.5 = borderline (within ±2 °C of a boundary)
            0.0 = outside range — triggers REJECT regardless of other scores
    warnings : list of strings describing any issues found
    """
    warnings: list[str] = []

    if not profile.safe_temp_range.contains(temp):
        # Temperature is outside the safe window — hard food-safety failure.
        # This check happens before the borderline check because contains()
        # must be True for is_borderline() to be meaningful.
        warnings.append(
            f"Temperature {temp:.1f} °C is OUTSIDE safe range "
            f"[{profile.safe_temp_range.min_c}, {profile.safe_temp_range.max_c}] °C"
        )
        return 0.0, warnings

    if profile.safe_temp_range.is_borderline(temp):
        # Temperature is technically safe but close to a boundary.
        # Score 0.5 tells the bin selector to prefer a safer fallback bin
        # and lowers the composite confidence.
        warnings.append(
            f"Temperature {temp:.1f} °C is borderline near range boundary "
            f"[{profile.safe_temp_range.min_c}, {profile.safe_temp_range.max_c}] °C"
        )
        return 0.5, warnings

    # Temperature is safely within range — full score, no warnings.
    return 1.0, warnings


def _score_perishability(
    profile: FoodProfile,
    hours_since_harvest: float,
) -> tuple[float, int, list[str]]:
    """
    Evaluate how much of the item's shelf life has already elapsed.

    Returns
    -------
    freshness_score : 0.0 (expired) → 1.0 (just harvested)
    urgency         : 1–10 priority for belt scheduling
                      high perishability + little life left = 10
    warnings        : list of any shelf-life alerts
    """
    warnings: list[str] = []

    # Guard against bad catalog data — shelf life of 0 would cause division by zero.
    if profile.shelf_life_hours <= 0:
        return 0.0, 10, ["Invalid shelf_life_hours in catalog (≤ 0) — treated as expired"]

    # remaining_fraction: 1.0 = just harvested, 0.0 = at exactly the shelf life limit
    # max(..., 0.0) clamps negative values — an item past its limit gets fraction = 0.
    remaining_fraction = max(0.0, 1.0 - (hours_since_harvest / profile.shelf_life_hours))

    if remaining_fraction == 0.0:
        # Item has hit or exceeded its shelf life — the caller will reject it.
        warnings.append(
            f"Item has used {hours_since_harvest:.1f} h of "
            f"{profile.shelf_life_hours:.1f} h shelf life — EXPIRED"
        )

    # urgency_priority formula:
    #   • Start at base 1 (minimum urgency).
    #   • Add (perishability × fraction of life already consumed).
    #   • A chicken breast (perishability=10) at 90% elapsed → raw ≈ 10, priority 10.
    #   • Canned beans (perishability=1) at 1% elapsed → raw ≈ 0.01, priority 1.
    raw_urgency     = profile.perishability * (1.0 - remaining_fraction)
    urgency_priority = min(10, max(1, round(raw_urgency + 1)))  # clamp to 1–10

    return remaining_fraction, urgency_priority, warnings


def _score_regional(
    profile: FoodProfile,
    region: Region,
) -> tuple[float, list[str]]:
    """
    Look up how well this food type survives in the current region.

    Returns
    -------
    score    : 0.0 (very poorly suited) → 1.0 (ideal region)
    warnings : advisory warning if score is below 0.4
    """
    warnings: list[str] = []

    # .get() with default 0.5 handles any region not listed in the profile
    # (neutral assumption rather than failing or penalising heavily).
    score = profile.regional_scores.get(region, 0.5)

    if score < 0.4:
        # Below 0.4 the item is likely to degrade faster here than expected.
        # This is advisory — it does NOT alone cause rejection or quarantine,
        # but it does reduce confidence and may be surfaced to an operator
        # for redistribution decisions.
        warnings.append(
            f"Low regional suitability ({score:.2f}) for region '{region.value}' — "
            f"consider redistributing to a better-suited facility"
        )

    return score, warnings


def _select_bin(
    profile:       FoodProfile,
    temp_score:    float,
    regional_score: float,
) -> tuple[Optional[Bin], float]:
    """
    Choose the most appropriate bin from the food's ordered allowed_bins list.

    Logic
    -----
    - Start with the most-preferred bin (index 0).
    - If temperature is borderline (score 0.5) AND a fallback exists, step
      to the second-choice bin — it is safer to use a more conservative
      destination when the reading is ambiguous.
    - Reduce confidence further if regional suitability is poor, because
      the item may not last as long as expected even in the chosen bin.

    Returns
    -------
    bin        : chosen Bin enum value (or None if allowed_bins is empty)
    confidence : 1.0 = first-choice bin, 0.6 = fallback bin;
                 further reduced if regional score < 0.4
    """
    if not profile.allowed_bins:
        # Catalog data error — no valid bin defined for this food type.
        return None, 0.0

    chosen_bin  = profile.allowed_bins[0]   # start with most-preferred choice
    confidence  = 1.0                       # full confidence for first-choice bin

    if temp_score == 0.5 and len(profile.allowed_bins) > 1:
        # Borderline temperature — step down to the secondary bin.
        # Example: strawberry at 3.8 °C (borderline near max 4.0 °C) goes
        # to freezer instead of refrigeration to be safe.
        chosen_bin  = profile.allowed_bins[1]
        confidence  = 0.6   # reduced because we used a non-preferred destination

    if regional_score < 0.4:
        # Poor regional fit — reduce confidence further, but don't change the
        # bin (the regional issue is about longevity, not immediate safety).
        confidence = max(0.3, confidence - 0.2)

    return chosen_bin, confidence


def _select_action(
    profile:     FoodProfile,
    destination: Bin,
    temp_score:  float,
    urgency:     int,
) -> Action:
    """
    Translate scores and flags into a single physical hardware command.

    Rules are evaluated in strict priority order:
      1. Unsafe temperature (score 0.0) → always open the reject chute.
      2. Fragile item OR quarantine destination → robotic arm for precision.
      3. Very high urgency (≥ 9) → stop belt for careful hand-off.
      4. Everything else → passive lane divert (fastest, default path).
    """
    if temp_score == 0.0:
        # Temperature check already failed — this item is being rejected.
        # Open the reject trapdoor directly; no other action is appropriate.
        return Action.REJECT_CHUTE

    if profile.requires_robotic_arm or destination == Bin.QUARANTINE:
        # Fragile items: divert gate impact would cause physical damage.
        # Quarantine: operator needs to inspect the item in place — robotic
        # arm places it carefully into the quarantine bin without dropping.
        return Action.ROBOTIC_ARM

    if urgency >= 9:
        # Near-expiry, high-perishability item — halt the belt so the item
        # doesn't get lost in the queue. The arm or operator picks immediately.
        return Action.CONVEYOR_STOP

    # Default: passive gate divert. Fastest path, no motor wear, no arm cycle.
    return Action.DIVERT_LANE


# COMMENTS-Section 8 — Edge-Case Handlers
# Four specialised functions for handling specific failure modes that would cause the pipeline to break if implemented inside. All return a ready-to-use SortDecision object and short-circuit the sort_item() function.

#_handle_unknown_food(sample) — triggered whenever the food type string is not found in FOOD_CATALOG. Unable to do any reasonable action as it lacks profile information about the type and can't access temperature/bin data. 
# Routes to quarantine, confidence 0.0, condition BAD.
#_handle_expired_item(sample, profile) — triggered whenever the calculated remaining_fraction <= 0.0, which means the item is expired past its shelf life period. 
# Routes to reject chute unconditionally (confidence 1.0, condition BAD) because expired items are always bad food.
#_handle_unsafe_temperature(sample, profile) — triggered whenever temperature score is 0.0, indicating that the food is outside the safety range entirely. 
# Again a direct hard rule: route to reject chute (confidence 1.0, condition BAD) because this is unsafe.
#_handle_conflicting_criteria(sample, profile, ...) — triggered whenever all criteria individually pass the hard stops but combined composite confidence is still <0.4. 
# Catch-all handler that deals with edge cases such as temperature borderline + bad regional suitability + high perishability. Routes to quarantine with confidence 0.35 (condition CRITICAL for human review).

#Feeds into: each function in this list is called by sort_item() in the respective step of its pipeline. If invoked, its output is returned from sort_item() immediately, bypassing composite confidence check altogether.


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 8 — EDGE-CASE HANDLERS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# These four functions handle specific failure modes that would break the
# main decision pipeline if handled inline. Isolating them keeps sort_item()
# readable and makes the failure modes independently testable.

def _handle_unknown_food(sample: FoodSample) -> SortDecision:
    """
    Called when food_type is not found in FOOD_CATALOG.
    No safe temperature range exists → quarantine for human inspection.
    Confidence is explicitly 0.0 — the machine has no information to reason with.
    """
    logger.warning(
        "Unknown food type '%s' (item %s) — routing to quarantine",
        sample.food_type, sample.item_id
    )
    return SortDecision(
        item_id=sample.item_id,
        destination=Bin.QUARANTINE,
        action=Action.ROBOTIC_ARM,          # careful placement for unknown item
        priority=5,                         # mid-priority — inspect soon but not emergency
        confidence=0.0,                     # zero confidence: engine has no basis for a decision
        reason=(
            f"Food type '{sample.food_type}' not found in catalog. "
            f"Quarantined for human inspection and catalog update."
        ),
        condition=FoodCondition.BAD,        # unknown item cannot be confirmed safe
        warnings=[f"Unrecognised food type: '{sample.food_type}'"],
    )


def _handle_expired_item(sample: FoodSample, profile: FoodProfile) -> SortDecision:
    """
    Called when the item has exceeded its shelf life.
    Shelf-life expiry is always a hard reject — no other criteria matter.
    Confidence 1.0 because this is a deterministic rule, not a probabilistic score.
    """
    logger.warning(
        "EXPIRED: %s (item %s) — %.1f h elapsed vs %.1f h max",
        profile.name, sample.item_id,
        sample.hours_since_harvest, profile.shelf_life_hours
    )
    return SortDecision(
        item_id=sample.item_id,
        destination=Bin.REJECT,
        action=Action.REJECT_CHUTE,
        priority=10,                        # process immediately — expired item on belt is a liability
        confidence=1.0,                     # certain: rule-based, not probabilistic
        reason=(
            f"{profile.name} is expired: {sample.hours_since_harvest:.1f} h elapsed "
            f"vs {profile.shelf_life_hours:.1f} h maximum shelf life."
        ),
        condition=FoodCondition.BAD,        # expired = definitively bad
        warnings=["Item past shelf life — REJECTED"],
    )


def _handle_unsafe_temperature(sample: FoodSample, profile: FoodProfile) -> SortDecision:
    """
    Called when the measured temperature is outside the safe range (not borderline).
    Temperature failure is always a hard reject — food may already be spoiling or frozen.
    """
    logger.warning(
        "UNSAFE TEMP: %s at %.1f °C (safe: %.1f–%.1f °C) (item %s)",
        profile.name, sample.measured_temp_c,
        profile.safe_temp_range.min_c, profile.safe_temp_range.max_c,
        sample.item_id
    )
    return SortDecision(
        item_id=sample.item_id,
        destination=Bin.REJECT,
        action=Action.REJECT_CHUTE,
        priority=10,
        confidence=1.0,
        reason=(
            f"{profile.name} measured at {sample.measured_temp_c:.1f} °C, "
            f"outside safe range [{profile.safe_temp_range.min_c}, "
            f"{profile.safe_temp_range.max_c}] °C. Rejected for food safety."
        ),
        condition=FoodCondition.BAD,        # unsafe temperature = bad regardless of age
        warnings=["Temperature outside safe range — REJECTED"],
    )


def _handle_conflicting_criteria(
    sample:      FoodSample,
    profile:     FoodProfile,
    temp_score:  float,
    reg_score:   float,
    urgency:     int,
    warnings:    list[str],
) -> SortDecision:
    """
    Called when all individual criteria pass but the composite confidence
    falls below CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD (0.40).
    This is the safety net for subtle combinations — e.g., borderline
    temperature + poor regional fit + high perishability together produce
    a confidence too low to trust an automatic placement.
    Routes to QUARANTINE so a human can make the final call.
    """
    logger.warning(
        "LOW CONFIDENCE: %s (item %s) temp=%.2f regional=%.2f urgency=%d — quarantined",
        profile.name, sample.item_id, temp_score, reg_score, urgency
    )
    return SortDecision(
        item_id=sample.item_id,
        destination=Bin.QUARANTINE,
        action=Action.ROBOTIC_ARM,
        priority=urgency,
        confidence=0.35,    # fixed low value — signals ambiguity to monitoring systems
        reason=(
            f"{profile.name} has conflicting sort signals: "
            f"temp_score={temp_score:.2f}, regional={reg_score:.2f}, urgency={urgency}. "
            f"Confidence too low for automatic placement — quarantined for human review."
        ),
        condition=FoodCondition.CRITICAL,   # conflicting signals → treat as critical until inspected
        warnings=warnings,
    )

# COMMENTS-Section 9 — Core Sorting Pipeline Function (sort_item)
# The one-and-only function that hardware integrators can call. Accepts a single food item, calls all other helpers in its 8-steps pipeline, and returns a SortDecision result.

# Step 0 — resolves food type name string from FOOD_CATALOG into its canonical form (all lowercase, whitespace stripped). If not present, calls _handle_unknown_food() and returns its output.
# Step 1 — calls _score_perishability() to calculate remaining_percentage. If it is 0.0 or lower, the item is expired and must be routed to reject chute. Calls _handle_expired_item() and exits.
# Step 2 — calls _score_temperature() to validate temperature reading. If it is fully unsafe, calls _handle_unsafe_temperature() and exits.
# Step 3 — calls _score_regional(). No early exit possible here, only generates warnings.
# Step 4 — calls _select_bin() to choose the destination. Fallback: if the profile does not have bins, calls _handle_conflicting_criteria() and exits.
# Step 5 — calls _select_action() to choose hardware command.
# Step 6 — calculates composite confidence as weighted average: temperature 35%, destination 30%, perishability 20%, regional 15%. Combined with bin confidence.
# Step 7 — if composite confidence < 0.40, calls _handle_conflicting_criteria() and exits.
# Step 8 — calculates item's condition label using assess_food_condition() and assembles SortDecision from the collected information, logging it. Returns output.

# Feeds into: called once per item inside sort_batch() (Section 10). In turn, the __main__ code path (Section 14) invokes sort_batch().



# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 9 — CORE SORT FUNCTION
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD = 0.40     # below this → quarantine, never auto-place


def sort_item(sample: FoodSample) -> SortDecision:
    """
    Primary entry point for the sorting engine.

    Takes one FoodSample (from the sensor/vision layer) and evaluates all
    four criteria to produce a SortDecision ready for hardware execution.

    The pipeline runs in strict priority order so that hard safety failures
    (expiry, unsafe temperature) are caught before the more nuanced scoring.

    Parameters
    ----------
    sample : FoodSample   — the incoming item with all sensor readings

    Returns
    -------
    SortDecision          — destination + action + full scoring metadata
    """

    # ── Step 0: Catalog lookup ────────────────────────────────────────────
    # Normalise the food type string (lowercase + strip whitespace) so minor
    # formatting differences in the upstream barcode/vision output don't
    # cause false "unknown" results.
    profile = FOOD_CATALOG.get(sample.food_type.lower().strip())

    if profile is None:
        # No profile means we have no safe temperature range, no bin list —
        # nothing to reason with. Quarantine immediately rather than guess.
        return _handle_unknown_food(sample)

    all_warnings: list[str] = []   # accumulate warnings across all steps

    # ── Step 1: Perishability / shelf-life check ──────────────────────────
    # Checked BEFORE temperature because an expired item is rejected
    # regardless of its temperature — checking temperature first would waste
    # a potential hard reject on a sensor reading that doesn't matter.
    freshness_score, urgency, peri_warnings = _score_perishability(
        profile, sample.hours_since_harvest
    )
    all_warnings.extend(peri_warnings)

    if freshness_score <= 0.0:
        # remaining_fraction = 0 means item is at or past its shelf life.
        return _handle_expired_item(sample, profile)

    # ── Step 2: Temperature check ─────────────────────────────────────────
    # A score of 0.0 is an immediate hard reject.
    # A score of 0.5 (borderline) continues to step 3 but will de-prefer
    # the primary bin in step 4 and reduce composite confidence.
    temp_score, temp_warnings = _score_temperature(profile, sample.measured_temp_c)
    all_warnings.extend(temp_warnings)

    if temp_score == 0.0:
        return _handle_unsafe_temperature(sample, profile)

    # ── Step 3: Regional suitability ──────────────────────────────────────
    # Advisory only — a low regional score generates a warning and reduces
    # confidence but never alone causes rejection. A facility might store a
    # food in a suboptimal region if it's the only option; the engine flags
    # it for the operator but still routes the item.
    reg_score, reg_warnings = _score_regional(profile, sample.current_region)
    all_warnings.extend(reg_warnings)

    # ── Step 4: Bin selection (destination compatibility) ─────────────────
    # Walks the food's ordered allowed_bins list. Borderline temperature
    # and low regional score both feed into this decision.
    destination, bin_confidence = _select_bin(profile, temp_score, reg_score)

    if destination is None:
        # Catalog data error — allowed_bins is empty for this food type.
        all_warnings.append("No allowed bins defined in food profile — catalog data error.")
        return _handle_conflicting_criteria(
            sample, profile, temp_score, reg_score, urgency, all_warnings
        )

    # ── Step 5: Physical action ───────────────────────────────────────────
    # Converts all collected information into a single hardware command.
    action = _select_action(profile, destination, temp_score, urgency)

    # ── Step 6: Composite confidence score ────────────────────────────────
    # Weighted sum across all four criterion scores.
    # destination_score: 1.0 if we got the first-choice bin, 0.7 if fallback.
    # freshness_score is already 0–1 from _score_perishability.
    destination_score    = 1.0 if destination == profile.allowed_bins[0] else 0.7
    freshness_normalised = min(1.0, freshness_score)    # safety clamp, should already be 0–1

    composite = (
        CRITERION_WEIGHTS["temperature"]   * temp_score           +
        CRITERION_WEIGHTS["destination"]   * destination_score     +
        CRITERION_WEIGHTS["perishability"] * freshness_normalised  +
        CRITERION_WEIGHTS["regional"]      * reg_score
    )
    # Blend composite with bin_confidence (already reflects temperature and
    # regional penalties from _select_bin). Average of the two gives a score
    # that combines all four criteria with the bin-selection logic.
    final_confidence = round((composite + bin_confidence) / 2.0, 3)

    # ── Step 7: Low-confidence guard ──────────────────────────────────────
    # If no single criterion failed hard but the combination produces a
    # confidence below the threshold, override to quarantine.
    # This is the catch-all for subtle combinations the hard-stop checks
    # in steps 1–2 didn't catch.
    if final_confidence < CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD:
        return _handle_conflicting_criteria(
            sample, profile, temp_score, reg_score, urgency, all_warnings
        )

    # ── Step 8: Assemble and return the decision ──────────────────────────
    reason = (
        f"{profile.name} → {destination.value} via {action.value} | "
        f"temp={temp_score:.2f}  freshness={freshness_score:.2f}  "
        f"regional={reg_score:.2f}  urgency={urgency}/10  "
        f"confidence={final_confidence:.3f}"
    )
    logger.info("SORT | item=%-10s | %s", sample.item_id, reason)

    # Assess human-readable food condition using the scores already computed.
    # This does not change the routing decision — it attaches a display label.
    condition, _cond_desc = assess_food_condition(
        sample, freshness_score, temp_score, destination
    )

    return SortDecision(
        item_id=sample.item_id,
        destination=destination,
        action=action,
        priority=urgency,
        confidence=final_confidence,
        reason=reason,
        condition=condition,
        warnings=all_warnings,
    )


# COMMENTS-Section 10 — Batch Sort Utility (sort_batch)
# This single function sorts a batch of food samples. Used when several items are processed simultaneously after resolving jam/unloading pallet.

# Calls sort_item() for every sample in the input list and gathers the resulting decisions. Orders them by priority descending (higher perishability comes first) for faster processing in execute_decision(). 
# The built-in sort function in Python is stable, so items with equal priority retain their original intake order (FIFO per priority level).

#Feeds into: executed by the __main__ function (Section 14). Its output is fed into execute_decision() (Section 11) and print_dashboard() (Section 13).


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 10 — BATCH SORT UTILITY
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def sort_batch(samples: list[FoodSample]) -> list[SortDecision]:
    """
    Sort a list of FoodSamples and return decisions ordered by descending
    priority (most urgent first).

    Use this when multiple items have accumulated in the intake buffer —
    for example after a conveyor jam clears or during a pallet scan.
    The belt controller should execute decisions in the order returned:
    highest priority (most perishable / most urgent) gets routed first.

    For single-item real-time throughput, call sort_item() directly.
    """
    # Process every sample through the full decision engine
    decisions = [sort_item(s) for s in samples]

    # Sort by priority descending so the most urgent items are at index 0.
    # Python's sort is stable — equal-priority items keep their intake order,
    # which is correct (FIFO within the same urgency tier).
    return sorted(decisions, key=lambda d: d.priority, reverse=True)


# COMMENTS-Section 11 — Simulated Hardware Driver Layer
# These four driver functions would normally communicate with hardware using serial interface, CAN bus, PLC controller, etc. Currently, each prints what it would be doing and simulates actual actuation delay with time.sleep().

# driver_divert_lane(decision) — simulated 50 ms pneumatic gate pulse.
# driver_conveyor_stop(decision) — simulated 80 ms ramp-down of the motor.
# driver_robotic_arm(decision) — simulated 120 ms robot pick-and-place cycle.
# driver_reject_chute(decision) — simulated 60 ms solenoid open-close cycle.

# ACTION_DRIVERS is a driver dispatch table — a regular Python dictionary with the action enum value as the key and the driver function as the value. 
# When expanding the system with additional actions, it is enough to write a new driver function and register its entry in the table. sort_item() and execute_decision() require no changes.
# execute_decision(decision) queries ACTION_DRIVERS table and calls the correct driver.

# Feeds into: called by execute_decision() (Section 11) as part of the hardware execution loop in the __main__ code (Section 14).



# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 11 — SIMULATED HARDWARE DRIVER LAYER
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# In a production system these functions would send serial/CAN bus/PLC
# commands to the actual hardware. Here they print what they would do,
# simulating the timing and confirmation messages a real driver returns.

def driver_divert_lane(decision: SortDecision) -> None:
    """
    Simulates flipping a pneumatic gate to divert the item to its bin lane.
    Real implementation: send a 24 V pulse to the gate solenoid for 150 ms,
    then read back the gate-closed limit switch to confirm.
    """
    print(
        f"  [DRIVER] DIVERT LANE → {decision.destination.value} "
        f"(item {decision.item_id})"
    )
    time.sleep(0.05)    # simulate 50 ms gate actuation latency
    print(f"  [DRIVER] Gate confirmed closed — item cleared to lane.")


def driver_conveyor_stop(decision: SortDecision) -> None:
    """
    Simulates halting the conveyor belt at the sort station.
    Real implementation: ramp the belt motor down to 0 RPM over 200 ms,
    wait for the encoder to confirm stopped, then signal the pick station.
    """
    print(
        f"  [DRIVER] CONVEYOR STOP — holding belt for item {decision.item_id} "
        f"(priority {decision.priority}/10)"
    )
    time.sleep(0.08)    # simulate ramp-down latency
    print(f"  [DRIVER] Belt at 0 RPM. Pick station armed.")
    # In real code: after pick confirmation, call driver_belt_resume()


def driver_robotic_arm(decision: SortDecision) -> None:
    """
    Simulates triggering a full robotic pick-and-place cycle.
    Real implementation: send a PICK command with bin ID and item coordinates
    to the arm controller over TCP, await ACK, then await PLACED confirmation.
    """
    print(
        f"  [DRIVER] ROBOTIC ARM → pick item {decision.item_id} "
        f"→ place in {decision.destination.value}"
    )
    time.sleep(0.12)    # simulate arm travel + place cycle time
    print(f"  [DRIVER] Arm cycle complete. Item placed. Arm returning to home.")


def driver_reject_chute(decision: SortDecision) -> None:
    """
    Simulates opening the reject trapdoor under the belt.
    Real implementation: energise the chute solenoid, wait 300 ms,
    de-energise (spring returns chute to closed), log item serial as REJECTED.
    """
    print(
        f"  [DRIVER] REJECT CHUTE OPEN — dropping item {decision.item_id} "
        f"({'EXPIRED' if 'shelf life' in decision.reason else 'UNSAFE TEMP'})"
    )
    time.sleep(0.06)
    print(f"  [DRIVER] Chute closed. Item logged as rejected.")


# Dispatch table: maps Action enum → driver function.
# Using a dict instead of if/elif means adding a new Action only requires
# adding an entry here and writing the driver function — sort_item() doesn't
# need to change.
ACTION_DRIVERS: dict[Action, callable] = {
    Action.DIVERT_LANE:  driver_divert_lane,
    Action.CONVEYOR_STOP: driver_conveyor_stop,
    Action.ROBOTIC_ARM:  driver_robotic_arm,
    Action.REJECT_CHUTE: driver_reject_chute,
}


def execute_decision(decision: SortDecision) -> None:
    """
    Dispatch a SortDecision to the correct hardware driver.
    This is what the main control loop calls after sort_item() returns.
    """
    driver_fn = ACTION_DRIVERS.get(decision.action)
    if driver_fn is None:
        # Unknown action — should never happen if Enums are used correctly,
        # but guard against it anyway to avoid a silent no-op.
        logger.error("No driver found for action '%s' (item %s)", decision.action, decision.item_id)
        return
    driver_fn(decision)


# COMMENTS-Section 12 - Simulated Sensor / Conveyor Feed
# Three simulated functions which emulate the capabilities of actual hardware sensors used during production.
# simulate_ir_sensor(profile, scenario) creates an artificial IR temperature reading by calculating the midpoint of the temperature range for the food and adding noise (+/-0.5 °C). 
# The scenario determines one of four possible outcomes; "normal" (midpoint + noise), "borderline" (±1.5 °C of upper limit), "unsafe" (8–15 °C above upper limit), and "frozen" (5–10 °C below lower limit).
# simulate_harvest_hours(profile, freshness) creates an artificial elapsed-time reading by calculating a fraction of shelf_life_hours. 
# "fresh" is 10–25% consumption, "aging" is 50–70%, "expiring" is 85-95%, and "expired" is 110–130% of the upper limit.
# generate_sample_batch(region) constructs the complete 12-item test batch which exercises all possible conditions; normal food sorts, borderline temperature reading, unsafe temperature reading, expired food item, near expiration, and unknown food item.
# Inputs into: generate_sample_batch() is called from the __main__ block (Section 14) to create the batch that sort_batch() will process.


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 12 — SIMULATED SENSOR / CONVEYOR FEED
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# In production these functions would be replaced by real sensor drivers.
# Here they generate realistic synthetic readings to exercise every code path.

def simulate_ir_sensor(profile: FoodProfile, scenario: str = "normal") -> float:
    """
    Simulate an IR temperature sensor reading for a food item.

    Scenarios
    ---------
    "normal"     — temperature near the midpoint of the safe range ± small noise
    "borderline" — temperature within 1.5 °C of the upper boundary
    "unsafe"     — temperature above the upper boundary by 8–15 °C
    "frozen"     — temperature below the lower boundary (useful for fresh items)

    In real hardware: read a 10-bit ADC value from the MLX90614 IR sensor,
    apply the calibration polynomial, compensate for ambient temperature drift.
    """
    mid = (profile.safe_temp_range.min_c + profile.safe_temp_range.max_c) / 2.0
    noise = random.uniform(-0.5, 0.5)   # ±0.5 °C simulates sensor measurement noise

    if scenario == "borderline":
        # Within 1.5 °C of the upper limit — triggers borderline path
        return round(profile.safe_temp_range.max_c - 1.5 + noise, 1)
    elif scenario == "unsafe":
        # 8–15 °C above the upper limit — triggers reject path
        return round(profile.safe_temp_range.max_c + random.uniform(8, 15) + noise, 1)
    elif scenario == "frozen":
        # 5–10 °C below lower limit — triggers reject path for non-frozen foods
        return round(profile.safe_temp_range.min_c - random.uniform(5, 10) + noise, 1)
    else:
        # Normal: midpoint with noise — should produce a clean sort
        return round(mid + noise, 1)


def simulate_harvest_hours(profile: FoodProfile, freshness: str = "fresh") -> float:
    """
    Simulate how many hours have elapsed since this item was harvested/produced.

    freshness options
    -----------------
    "fresh"    — 10–25 % of shelf life elapsed (newly arrived stock)
    "aging"    — 50–70 % of shelf life elapsed (mid-cycle stock)
    "expiring" — 85–95 % of shelf life elapsed (near end of life)
    "expired"  — 110–130 % of shelf life elapsed (past the limit)

    In real hardware: read the harvest timestamp from the RFID tag or
    QR/barcode label, subtract from the current UTC clock.
    """
    if freshness == "fresh":
        fraction = random.uniform(0.10, 0.25)
    elif freshness == "aging":
        fraction = random.uniform(0.50, 0.70)
    elif freshness == "expiring":
        fraction = random.uniform(0.85, 0.95)
    else:  # expired
        fraction = random.uniform(1.10, 1.30)

    # Return hours, rounded to one decimal place
    return round(profile.shelf_life_hours * fraction, 1)


def generate_sample_batch(region: Region = Region.TEMPERATE) -> list[FoodSample]:
    """
    Generate a representative batch of 12 synthetic food samples covering
    all major code paths in the sort engine.

    In production this function would not exist — FoodSamples would come
    directly from the vision system and sensor array for each real item.
    """
    food_types  = list(FOOD_CATALOG.keys())
    item_count  = 0

    samples: list[FoodSample] = []

    def make(food_type: str, temp_scenario: str, freshness: str, note: str) -> FoodSample:
        nonlocal item_count
        item_count += 1
        profile = FOOD_CATALOG[food_type]
        temp    = simulate_ir_sensor(profile, temp_scenario)
        hours   = simulate_harvest_hours(profile, freshness)
        item_id = f"ITM-{item_count:04d}"
        logger.debug("Generated sample: %s %s temp=%.1f h=%.1f [%s]",
                     item_id, food_type, temp, hours, note)
        return FoodSample(food_type, temp, region, hours, item_id)

    # One sample per food type with varied conditions
    samples.append(make("strawberry",     "normal",     "fresh",    "nominal fresh strawberry"))
    samples.append(make("banana",         "normal",     "aging",    "mid-cycle banana"))
    samples.append(make("chicken_breast", "borderline", "fresh",    "borderline temp chicken"))
    samples.append(make("canned_beans",   "normal",     "fresh",    "nominal canned beans"))
    samples.append(make("ice_cream",      "unsafe",     "aging",    "unsafe temp ice cream"))
    samples.append(make("mango",          "normal",     "expiring", "near-expiry mango"))
    samples.append(make("whole_milk",     "normal",     "aging",    "aging whole milk"))
    samples.append(make("flour",          "normal",     "fresh",    "nominal flour"))
    samples.append(make("salmon_fillet",  "borderline", "expiring", "borderline + near-expiry salmon"))
    samples.append(make("chicken_breast", "normal",     "expired",  "expired chicken — should reject"))
    samples.append(make("strawberry",     "unsafe",     "fresh",    "unsafe temp strawberry — reject"))

    # One unknown food type to exercise the quarantine path
    item_count += 1
    samples.append(FoodSample("dragon_fruit", 18.0, region, 10.0, f"ITM-{item_count:04d}"))

    return samples


# COMMENTS-Section 13 – Dashboard / Summary Printer (print_dashboard)
# Formates and prints three panels to the terminal after a batch of food is sorted.
# Results Sort Panel – one block per item (prioritised sorted in the order in which they were sorted), containing: condition symbol and its level, destination bin, hardware action, priority, a bar chart (of 20 blocks wide) representing confidence, reason string and warnings.
# Summary Batch Panel – provides the totals for: total number sorted, total sorted %, reject for food safety %, quarantine %, and the average confidence for the batch. 
# Additionally, it prints the Bin Fill report, displaying the number of food items that were sorted into each bin using a proportional bar.
# Food Condition Report Panel – classifies all items in the batch based on the severity of the Food Condition level (from GOOD to BAD), printing: total items of this category (% of the batch), recommended operator handling action (using CONDITION_ACTIONS dictionary), and the item IDs and food names at this level (word wrapped up to 72 characters). 
# The function uses a nested helper function _food_name() to safely extract the food type name from the reason string in the decision object, even for the special unknown food type messages.
# Feed from: called once by the __main__ block (Section 14) after executing all hardware actions.


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 13 — DASHBOARD / SUMMARY PRINTER
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Prints a formatted terminal dashboard after processing a batch.
# In production this output would go to a SCADA screen or be serialised
# to JSON and sent to the monitoring service.

def print_dashboard(decisions: list[SortDecision]) -> None:
    """Print a formatted summary of a batch of sort decisions."""

    LINE = "═" * 78

    # ── Per-item detail ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
    print(f"\n{LINE}")
    print("  FOOD SORTER PROTOTYPE  —  SORT RESULTS")
    print(LINE)

    for d in decisions:
        # Confidence bar — visual indicator scaled to 20 characters
        bar_len  = round(d.confidence * 20)
        bar      = "█" * bar_len + "░" * (20 - bar_len)
        conf_pct = round(d.confidence * 100)

        # Condition symbol — one-character visual status indicator
        cond     = d.condition or FoodCondition.BAD
        symbol   = CONDITION_SYMBOLS.get(cond, "?")

        print(f"\n  [{d.item_id}]")
        print(f"    Condition    : {symbol}  {cond.value}")
        print(f"    Destination  : {d.destination.value}")
        print(f"    Action       : {d.action.value}")
        print(f"    Priority     : {d.priority}/10")
        print(f"    Confidence   : [{bar}] {conf_pct:3d}%")
        print(f"    Reason       : {d.reason}")
        if d.warnings:
            for w in d.warnings:
                print(f"    ⚠ Warning    : {w}")

    # ── Aggregate statistics ──────────────────────────────────────────────
    total      = len(decisions)
    rejected   = sum(1 for d in decisions if d.destination == Bin.REJECT)
    quarantined = sum(1 for d in decisions if d.destination == Bin.QUARANTINE)
    sorted_ok  = total - rejected - quarantined
    avg_conf   = sum(d.confidence for d in decisions) / total if total else 0

    print(f"\n{LINE}")
    print("  BATCH SUMMARY")
    print(f"  {'Total items processed':<30} {total}")
    print(f"  {'Successfully sorted':<30} {sorted_ok}  "
          f"({round(sorted_ok / total * 100) if total else 0} %)")
    print(f"  {'Rejected (food safety)':<30} {rejected}  "
          f"({round(rejected / total * 100) if total else 0} %)")
    print(f"  {'Quarantined (low confidence)':<30} {quarantined}  "
          f"({round(quarantined / total * 100) if total else 0} %)")
    print(f"  {'Average confidence':<30} {avg_conf:.3f}")

    # Bin fill report
    bin_counts: dict[Bin, int] = {b: 0 for b in Bin}
    for d in decisions:
        bin_counts[d.destination] += 1

    print(f"\n  BIN FILL REPORT")
    for bin_val, count in bin_counts.items():
        if count > 0:
            bar = "█" * count + "░" * (total - count)
            print(f"  {bin_val.value:<25} [{bar}] {count}")

    # ── Food Condition Report ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    # Groups every item by its FoodCondition level and prints a summary table.
    # This is the section an operator or food safety auditor reads to quickly
    # understand the health of the current batch without looking at raw scores.
    #
    # For each condition level we print:
    #   • The symbol and level name
    #   • How many items are at that level and what percentage of the batch
    #   • Which specific items (by ID and food type) are at that level
    #   • The recommended handling action for that level

    print(f"\n{LINE}")
    print("  FOOD CONDITION REPORT")
    print(LINE)

    # Build a mapping of FoodCondition → list of decisions at that level.
    # We iterate through FoodCondition in severity order (best → worst) so the
    # report reads top-to-bottom from good news to bad news.
    condition_order = [
        FoodCondition.GOOD,
        FoodCondition.USE_SOON,
        FoodCondition.EXPIRING_SOON,
        FoodCondition.CRITICAL,
        FoodCondition.BAD,
    ]

    # Group decisions by condition level.
    # dict comprehension builds an empty list for every level upfront so levels
    # with zero items still appear in the report (makes it easier to confirm
    # nothing was missed).
    condition_groups: dict[FoodCondition, list[SortDecision]] = {
        level: [] for level in condition_order
    }
    for d in decisions:
        level = d.condition or FoodCondition.BAD   # treat None as BAD (safety default)
        condition_groups[level].append(d)

    for level in condition_order:
        group   = condition_groups[level]
        count   = len(group)
        pct     = round(count / total * 100) if total else 0
        symbol  = CONDITION_SYMBOLS[level]
        action  = CONDITION_ACTIONS[level]

        # Build a compact list of "ITM-NNNN (food_type)" strings for this level.
        # If there are no items at this level, print a dash so the row still
        # appears and the operator knows it was checked.

        def _food_name(d: SortDecision) -> str:
            # Normal sort reasons: "food_name → bin_name via action | ..."
            # Edge-case reasons (expired, unsafe): "food_name is expired..." or
            #   "food_name measured at..." — first word is always the food name.
            # Unknown-type reason: "Food type 'dragon_fruit' not found..."
            #   — word[0] is "Food", so extract the quoted name instead.
            first = d.reason.split()[0]
            if first == "Food":
                try:
                    return d.reason.split("'")[1]   # grabs text between first pair of quotes
                except IndexError:
                    return "unknown"
            return first

        if group:
            pass    # items printed in the loop below
        else:
            print(f"\n  {symbol}  {level.value:<15}  {count:2d} items  ({pct:3d} %)")
            print(f"     Action : {action}")
            print(f"     Items  : —")
            continue     # skip to next level — nothing to print

        print(f"\n  {symbol}  {level.value:<15}  {count:2d} items  ({pct:3d} %)")
        print(f"     Action : {action}")
        if group:
            # Wrap the items list at 72 characters for readability
            line_buf = "     Items  : "
            for i, d in enumerate(group):
                food_name = _food_name(d)
                entry     = f"{d.item_id} ({food_name})"
                if i < len(group) - 1:
                    entry += ",  "
                # Start a new indented line when the current line would overflow
                if len(line_buf) + len(entry) > 72:
                    print(line_buf.rstrip(", "))
                    line_buf = "             " + entry  # continuation indent
                else:
                    line_buf += entry
            print(line_buf)

    print(f"\n{LINE}\n")


# COMMENTS-Section 14 - Entry Point
# Entry point for the script, runs only when the file is executed as python food_sorter_prototype.py. Does the following in sequence:

# Ensures random.seed(42) is fixed to guarantee repeatable sensor output in case of demonstrations or debugging.
# generate_sample_batch(region=Region.TEMPERATE) creates a sample batch of 12 objects that hit all code paths.
# sort_batch(batch) applies all objects to the decision engine, producing a list of decisions ordered by priority.
# Loops over the decisions returned from the previous step, displays routing context for each item and executes execute_decision(decision).
# Finally calls print_dashboard(decisions) to generate full terminal dashboard.

# Calling flow: generate_sample_batch() -> sort_batch() -> execute_decision() -> print_dashboard().


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SECTION 14 — MAIN ENTRY POINT
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

if __name__ == "__main__":

    print("\n" + "═" * 78)
    print("  FOOD SORTING MACHINE — PROTOTYPE STARTUP")
    print("═" * 78)
    print("  Simulating conveyor belt feed in TEMPERATE region facility.\n")

    # ── Generate a synthetic batch of items ───────────────────────────────
    # In production: items arrive from the vision/sensor pipeline one at a time.
    # Here: generate_sample_batch() builds a representative set all at once.
    random.seed(42)     # fix the seed so results are reproducible for demo purposes
    batch = generate_sample_batch(region=Region.TEMPERATE)

    print(f"  {len(batch)} items detected on intake belt. Running sort engine...\n")

    # ── Run the batch sort engine ─────────────────────────────────────────
    # sort_batch() calls sort_item() on each sample, then orders results by
    # priority descending — most urgent items are executed first.
    decisions = sort_batch(batch)

    # ── Execute each decision through the simulated hardware drivers ──────
    # In production: this loop would run in the main control thread,
    # calling real driver functions that communicate with PLC/robot controllers.
    print("  Executing hardware actions (priority order):")
    print("  " + "─" * 60)

    for decision in decisions:
        print(
            f"\n  Routing [{decision.item_id}] — "
            f"priority {decision.priority}/10 — "
            f"confidence {decision.confidence:.2f}"
        )
        execute_decision(decision)  # calls the appropriate driver function

    # ── Print the terminal dashboard ──────────────────────────────────────
    print_dashboard(decisions)
